title: User-submitted feedback for UXUI-UXI-DELIVER
body:
Chris Lallathin (chris.lallathin@gmail.com) reported an issue.


Name: "Delivering assets"

Live URL: https://courses.thinkful.com/uxui-uxi-deliver-v1/checkpoint/5

Course code: UXUI-UXI-DELIVER

Content:


    With some Figma-based assignments, we are asked to share a link to EITHER our Figma or our Design Journal, while other times we are asked to simply share a link to our Design Journal. What is the thinking in this? Having consistency across ALL checkpoints should be a no-brainer as, yet again, it is a hallmark of good UX. This stands as yet another example, in a very long list of examples, of Thinkful not having fully adopted the basic tenants of UX (which they attempt to teach their students from a position of expertise).

body:
Monica Longmire (mlongmire@thinkful.com) reported an issue.


Name: "Introduction to the define phase"

Live URL: https://courses.thinkful.com/uxui-uxi-define-v1/checkpoint/1

Course code: UXUI-UXI-DEFINE

Content:


    Can we add an example or further elaborate on "technical user stories" in the following section?

Current:
Who creates user stories?
Writing user stories is typically assigned to a business analyst or UX researcher. Technical user stories may be handled by a developer. On many small UX or multidisciplinary teams, a UX researcher or UX designer can write them.

title: User-submitted feedback for UXUI-UXI-DEFINE
body:
Monica Longmire (mlongmire@thinkful.com) reported an issue.


Name: "Introduction to the define phase"

Live URL: https://courses.thinkful.com/uxui-uxi-define-v1/checkpoint/1

Course code: UXUI-UXI-DEFINE

Content:


    Some of these explanations can seem a bit vague and not all of the items listed were covered in great detail in the previous modules (specifically Functional Requirements, User Experience Requirements, Marketing Requirements, Service Maps). Can we add at least one example for each bulleted item in the section below?:

Inputs from UX intensive: Discover
Remember all of that hard work you put in to discover and evaluate the user during your work in UX intensive: Discover? Now you get to put it to good use.

Here's a review of typical design inputs:

Business requirements: These are provided by the business to document nontechnical requirements. The business requirements are generally collected by a business analyst.

Functional requirements: These are provided by the business or IT to document the technical requirements. The functional requirements are generally collected by a systems analyst.

User experience requirements: These are provided by the business and the user experience team to document specific experience requirements.

Branding requirements: These are typically provided by the client or marketing team. At smaller companies, product and UX/UI designers are sometimes responsible for developing the brand.

Personas: As you learned in the User personas checkpoint, the designer typically creates the personas. Research provides statistical data to help you validate your personas and better understand the users who you're designing for.

Journey maps: As you learned in the Experience and idea mapping checkpoint, the designer typically creates journey maps.

Empathy maps: As you learned in the Experience and idea mapping checkpoint, the designer sometimes creates empathy maps.

Marketing requirements: These are typically provided by the client to document how the product addresses user needs in the market.

Service maps: These are another type of UX map that a designer may create. They act as a counterpart to journey maps, focusing on the actions taken by the service provider rather than the user.

Name: "Wireframing: Case study and About page"

Live URL: https://courses.thinkful.com/uxui-portfolio-i-v2-v2/uuid/89614e31-a768-439d-922a-2b7d9a203f28?course_code=UX-301#review-752175

Course code: UXUI-PORTFOLIO-I-V2

Content:


    Did the student complete 80% of the checklists for case study and about page, and you indicated that it is "approved with changes", making it clear what needs to be changed? 
No
Graded by Aljo Labsan. 
Did 2 (two or less) criteria in the rubric table receive a "Developing"? 
No
Graded by Aljo Labsan. 
What the student did well 
Hi Alexander good job on the wireframing assignment, you have some good ideas and inspiration from a number of templates that you used to base your wireframes off of.
	Your about page is structured well and has a basic format and typography
	Good use of negative space between visual elements
Graded by Aljo Labsan. 
Required changes to pass the assessment 
On your notion journal when I click "Wireframing: Case Study And About Page" it did not have any content or figma link to the specific submission. Likewise some of the other link for your submissions do not have the relevant content in them. Please fix this so that we can grade your assignments
	https://share.getcloudapp.com/xQuYdl1j
The only other link that I was able to derive a wireframe relevant to this assignment was nested under "Planning" which had a Figma link to all of your other assignments. I presume the page "Wireraming and Content Home Page" is the specific submission you intended to submit and will use that as the basis of this revision. For reference I will link the Figma link here: https://www.figma.com/file/5yy8yM9sWwb39hBSgFq4Z1/Portfolio-I-Planning-AA?node-id=9%3A106
	You are lacking a mobile version of your wireframes for both your Portfolio & your About page. Add these two to the appropriate figma link
	There should be relevant content on both your About & your Case Study page. Currently there is no bio of you on your About page and there is no Case Study on your Case Study page
For your About page add the following:
	A biography of about 500 words that is well written and gives insight into who you are as a person and as a professional.
	Explain how you started in design, what motivates you & what design means to you.
	A professional photo of yourself
	A link to download your resume
	A mobile version of your About page Desktop wireframe
For your Case Study do the following:
	Add a mobile version of your Desktop wireframe
	You already have an About page, no need to reintroduce yourself again on the case study page
	Remove the gradients and other content leftover from a template of another designer that you used. It would be jarring to a client to see your name with someone else's email address and linkedin making them think you took their designs and copied it. 
	https://share.getcloudapp.com/4guOADnd - student design
	https://share.getcloudapp.com/mXu5RoJJ - derived design
	Highly recommend to revise your Case Study with its own Desktop & Mobile designs. Right now it looks exactly like another designers work
	https://share.getcloudapp.com/llunm174 - student design
	https://share.getcloudapp.com/KoulzGnv - derived design
	I have attached resources below to give you ideas on how to properly design on a responsive grid and examples of properly designed case studies. Use these resources as inspiration to create your own Case Study design. Do not copy an existing designers site, a potential client may notice this and it will reflect poorly on you as a UX/UI professional.
Graded by Aljo Labsan. 
Optional changes/ideas/improvements 
To give you an idea of how to properly structure your Case Study I have attached a number of resources to help you properly structure your designs
	https://medium.com/@drewmck/a-ui-designers-primer-to-responsive-grids-270b523e6fa2
	https://uxdesign.cc/responsive-grids-and-how-to-actually-use-them-970de4c16e01
	https://blog.uxfol.io/ux-portfolio-presentation/
	https://uxfol.io/showcase - Use this to learn from how other designers structure their case studies. You can use it as inspiration, do not copy it over exactly
Graded by Aljo Labsan. 
Theres a lack of language here that is not in a positive tone.  As a teacher/instructor that is supposed to encourage not poop on peoples dreams.  There needs to be a consistency that would want to be better and improve.  I would like there to be a hopeful tone on the writing. Not some candy concoction of something that seems passive aggressive in nature.

body:
Polina Nikolayev-Stair (pnikolayev-stair@thinkful.com) reported an issue.


Name: "Wireframing: Case study and About page"

Live URL: https://courses.thinkful.com/uxui-portfolio-i-v2-v2/checkpoint/6

Course code: UXUI-PORTFOLIO-I-V2

Content:


    Hi team - as a grader, I've been reviewing very half-baked wireframes for this checkpoint. I'm trying to figure out if it's the instructions or if students just want to jump ahead to designing in Webflow and are blowing this off.

A few issues that stand out to me:

- Under the "Graded assignment' header it says, "Create wireframes for the rest of your site."  but then it says 'This will include at least a case study page and an About page'. Every student thus far has only submitted the 'at least'. Can it be that there are no other wireframes for their portfolios?

- RE: "Be sure to include all required elements from the appropriate checklists." --- there is only one checklist in the checkpoint, should we be referring back to 19.3 for this one since they're adding the content of their case study to the wires? Or perhaps the checklist from 19.3 should be added here, as well?


- RE: "Present your work for feedback as described in the first checkpoint of this module."  --- The first checkpoint in the module is is 'Prepare your case studies'. Should the student be presenting their work somewhere else in addition to link submission?

Thank you!

Course code: UXUI-ORIENTATION-FLEX

Content:


    Maintain momentum with the Zeigarnik Effect. Todd Henry, the host of The Accidental Creative podcast, advises determining a next action at the end of every work session. This means you always know what you have to do next, which can keep uncertainty from stalling out your progress when you try to get started again. Your dashboard provides you with clear next steps in your program, but you can gain additional momentum by sketching out an idea of how you will work on the next part of your program. In addition to providing clear direction, this advice taps into the power of the Zeigarnik Effect, which Adam Grant describes in his TED Talk. Here's the tl;dr: the mind keeps thinking about unfinished business. Todd Henry's recommendation to make a plan for your next step can keep your mind considering how you'll move forward in your program.

title: User-submitted feedback for UXUI-UXI-DEVELOP
body:
Bayley Zannini (bayley.zannini@gmail.com) reported an issue.


Name: "Further developing your layout"

Live URL: https://courses.thinkful.com/uxui-uxi-develop-v1/checkpoint/5

Course code: UXUI-UXI-DEVELOP

Content:


    There is an opportunity to reorganize the curriculum to improve student productivity. By taking this module and placing it ahead of the previous module, the student would understand what they are designing (visually) better and have the opportunity to apply it to their original wireframes whilst they're getting feedback. With the auto-grade system, it is hard to tell if you're going backward on your progress. Especially because we've already gone as far as to add color, font, and graphics to our prototypes. Currently, we are rearranging wireframes/prototypes that have already been approved and only getting occasional feedback from our mentors. In summary, there is a possibility that having these lessons after the fact is counterproductive to a student's momentum.

title: User-submitted feedback for UXUI-TEAM-DEFINE
body:
Alexus Gibson (alexusleighgibson@gmail.com) reported an issue.


Name: "Extracting insights through critiques and choosing the right solution"

Live URL: https://courses.thinkful.com/uxui-team-define-v1/checkpoint/9

Course code: UXUI-TEAM-DEFINE

Content:


    Idk where else to put this, but this section was incredibly frustrating to read for a couple of reasons. 
1. I have had constructive feedback on the grand total of my assignments on maybe 5 things total in the 3 months in this program because everything is autograded. The amount of feedback and constructive is negligibly low, and to hear that I've had a healthy dose of it without people looking at anything more than 1 or 2 assignments and then the assessments is very frustrating. 
2. This article on constructive criticism goes against the feedback that's given on "UX as A DJ" Where an example of poor UX is described as: 

Example #4: iFly
The problem: What is an important goal of UX/UI designers? Avoid frictions where a user gets stuck. Sometimes it happens and you hope to catch it in user testing.

A terrible example of stupid friction: KLM's 50th anniversary website, iFly50.com, is a vertical scrolling website that showcases 50 travel destinations. In an otherwise minimal design, the site asks users to click and hold for a few seconds to view more photos. Seriously?

Hopefully that UX designer either switched professions or saw the light, because that is shameful friction. It's weird and also requires a totally unintuitive action of holding a button down like it's an ancient elevator. And, you get stuck all over the place.

I'm really not trying to be rude or mean but seeing so much contradiction while I'm trying to absorb all this information without much guidance is exhausting.

Name: "Web design: HTML containers"

Live URL: https://courses.thinkful.com/uxui-sp-fe-ii-v1/checkpoint/7

Course code: UXUI-SP-FE-II

Content:


    I am a TA/Mentor (Grace Cupat) - I just spent quite a bit of time helping a student on this and in the Github checkpoint where she was all kinds of lost. For this checkpoint the section that says: 

"Use this code sample to add the HTML containers around the existing content. Do not edit or worry about the CSS styles at this time, as all those styles will be explained in detail in the next checkpoints." 

She was under the assumption that she did not need to look at the CSS at all. So she was trying to Code the HTML without referring to the CSS. So I would suggest that instead of saying "Do not edit or worry about the CSS styles" it should be worded "Refer to the CSS to code the HTML, but do not change the CSS"

title: User-submitted feedback for UXUI-SP-VIS-I
body:
Michael  Morgan (mklmrgn@gmail.com) reported an issue.


Name: "Begin Designing the UI"

Live URL: https://courses.thinkful.com/uxui-sp-vis-i-v1/checkpoint/2

Course code: UXUI-SP-VIS-I

Content:


    Again the assignment makes no sense. Machine Learning??? Review the UX deliverables below??? Whats the assignment???

TOP OF PAGE:

Learning Objective: By the end of the checkpoint, students will be able to evaluate visual mockups content personalization, adaptive UI and interface inventories, and apply these techniques to the user interface they are being asked to design for this module.
You spent the last checkpoint creating a design brief, which allowed you to answer the big visual design questions that you need to focus on to build a great user interface, and hopefully you had fun making a mood board, establishing some of the look and feel that you want to bring to this design.
Now, it is time to make some choices. In this checkpoint, you will review and analyze machine learning, content personalization and adaptive UI. You will also reflect on interface inventories, and do your own for your real client app project, along with making some key decisions for the visual design process you are undertaking, in an assignment that looks like this:
1.	Review the UX deliverables below, including their wireframes and prototypes.
2.	Conduct an interface inventory.
3.	After taking screenshots of all the pieces, start categorizing everything to impose some order. This organizing and categorizing will lead to a better understanding of the different components you need to design. It will also aid in streamlining your different components by identifying shared patterns.
4.	Make some decisions, and start choosing which tools you will use to design your user interface; we recommend Figma, Adobe XD or Invision. You will use these as a rough base to build upon, keeping in mind that you are designing an interface for your unique user and a real client.

BOTTOM OF PAGE:

"Assignment
1.	Review the UX deliverables below, including their wireframes and prototypes.
1.	Review the target audience profile that the UX designers created, using the information gathered by the business analysts and UX researchers.
2.	Download the free Adobe XD UI Kits.
3.	Complete the tutorials on starting your design with UI Kits.
2.	Conduct an interface inventory.
0.	An interface inventory ensures that user interfaces are developed consistently within a comprehensive and considered framework. Just like a style guide  it should be a living document that is extensible, and grows as your product grows.
1.	Systematically take screenshots of everything you or your team has designed so far, and check for inconsistencies. Consider all the different components that comprise your user interface, including:
1.	Typography
1.	Headings and Subheadings
2.	Text Elements (Standfirsts, Paragraphs)
3.	Lists
2.	Images and Media
1.	Logos
2.	Iconography
3.	Images
3.	Forms
0.	Text Inputs
1.	Radio / Checkbox Inputs
2.	Select Menus"

title: User-submitted feedback for UXUI-SP-VIS-I
body:
Michael  Morgan (mklmrgn@gmail.com) reported an issue.


Name: "Intro Visual Design Specialization"

Live URL: https://courses.thinkful.com/uxui-sp-vis-i-v1/checkpoint/1

Course code: UXUI-SP-VIS-I

Content:


    The assignments are totally incoherent :(

THE BEGINNING OF THE MODULE (talks about our previous project):

"You spent the last module creating an awesome and dynamic portfolio, so lets keep adding to it during this specialization, and make sure you have some beautiful work to showcase as you leverage your way into a job.
In this first module, Visual Design Specialization I, you are going to get the chance to design the user interface for your real client app project that you researched, designed and tested during the team design phase.

In this checkpoint, you will be able to review how the visual design of a products user interface fits within the design process, along with branding and design systems, and we will evaluate the value of design briefs and mood boards to set the stage for your visual design, as you apply these techniques in a 3-part assignment to begin designing the user interface for your real client app:
1.	Review the Research (UX, User Research, Pattern Library, Etc.)
2.	Create a Design Brief Document (Defining the Why, How & What of the Scope)
3.	Make Your Mood Board (Pick Your Tools & Choose What To Include & Build It)


THE BOTTOM OF THE PAGE:
"Review the Research
1.	Review all the materials that our Ux Researcher and Business Analyst created (below). You will base your UI designs on these.
2.	Review the research and create a list of requirements that will help shape the UI.
3.	Visit pttrns.com, ui-patterns.com, or a similar site, and save 10 patterns to your private pattern library that you began populating in Module 3 and Module 6.
4.	Save 5 designs for inspiration, with at least one that incorporates machine learning.
5.	Evaluate the information architecture, content and visual design, focusing on why the designs offer solutions that will help you create an interface for _My Daily Nosh_, and note what you like, and what aspects you want to mimic and remix for this project.

User-submitted feedback for UXUI-FUN-DESIGN-AND-RESEARCH
body:
Bayley Zannini (bayley.zannini@gmail.com) reported an issue.


Name: "Understanding users"

Live URL: https://courses.thinkful.com/uxui-fun-design-and-research-v1/checkpoint/2

Course code: UXUI-FUN-DESIGN-AND-RESEARCH

Content:


    Knowledge learned in this checkpoint is not applied in the checkpoint's assignment.
---
I understood the lesson quite well. I took notes. Used given links. It was very helpful and I learned a lot. Though valuable information, I wasn't able to use it.

The assignment was to create a proto-persona. Knowing the value of a persona and creating an example of a person with goals, motivations, and frustrations are two VERY IMPORTANT but different things. I found my self getting very frustrated. I was barely given an outline of what to do in the description of the assignment. The only example in the entire checkpoint of a persona did not match the requirements of what the persona in the assignment needed to have. 

I'm a strong believer that if you are going to bring up a concern, you should also provide a solution. (Even if it isn't what everyone chooses in the end) I would have preferred to pick one of the topics that we learned about and written 250 words of how I can apply this knowledge in my designs or everyday life. 

I hope everything makes sense. Please reach out with any questions or comments. I hope this helps future students!

title: User-submitted feedback for UXUI-FUN-DESIGN-AND-RESEARCH
body:
Jonathan Canales (joncanales2@gmail.com) reported an issue.


Name: "Insight Translation"

Live URL: https://courses.thinkful.com/uxui-fun-design-and-research-v1/checkpoint/4

Course code: UXUI-FUN-DESIGN-AND-RESEARCH

Content:


    Question phrasing is odd and not exactly clear on what is happening. Disjunct from the rest of the text.

"1. Articulate and document your research question for your upcoming user study.

2. List the types of research you think will be appropriate for learning about a transportation mobile app experience."

This prompt is kind of setup in an ambiguous way where it isn't clear if these two things are linked or not i.e is the upcoming user study is in regards to a transportation mobile app experience? Also, am I supposed to be aware of an upcoming user study somewhere in the course work thus far?

It is entirely possible, I've missed something right in front of me while taking notes and drawing in Figma.
